e and performed plays, including Shakespearean productions, before mixed race audiences. Their audacity provoked feelings of excitement and hope among blacks, but often of disgust by many whites for whom the theater's existence epitomized the horrors of emancipation. Stories of Freedom in Black New York brilliantly intertwines black theater and urban life into a powerful interpretation of what the end of slavery meant for blacks, whites, and New York City itself. White's story of the emergence of free black culture offers a unique understanding of emancipation's impact on everyday life, and on the many forms freedom can take.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aAfrican American actorsxBiographyxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aAfrican American theaterxHistoryx19th centuryxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aAfrican AmericansxHistoryx19th centuryxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aAfrican AmericansxIntellectual lifex19th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxIntellectual lifexNew York (State)xNew York. 0aAfrican AmericansxSocial conditionsx19th centuryxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aSlaveryxSocial aspectsxHistoryx19th centuryxNew York (State)xNew York. 7aHISTORY / United States / Civil War Period (1850-1877).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674045149zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674045149423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674045149/original  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-075606-7  HUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)